-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 12 (0-11)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 2 (converged when consensus-score = 9 ≥ 8)
-- Cells evaluated: question, perspective-cto, perspective-senior,
--   perspective-junior, perspective-investor, mediate (×2),
--   revise-cto, revise-senior, revise-junior, revise-investor, synthesize
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: N-way parallel evaluation works naturally
--   Frames 1-4 evaluate four perspective cells independently. Confluence
--   guarantees the same mediation result regardless of evaluation order.
--   In a parallel runtime, all four could execute simultaneously.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: mediator pattern enables structured multi-agent negotiation
--   The mediator cell acts as a synchronization barrier: it waits for all N
--   perspectives, identifies common ground and disagreements, then enables
--   the revision cells. This is a reusable pattern for any N-party decision.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: ⊢∘ convergence via consensus score is judgment-gated
--   The convergence condition (consensus-score ≥ 8) is a semantic judgment,
--   not a structural check. The mediator must assess whether positions have
--   converged — this oracle is inherently soft. This is fine: the mediator
--   IS the oracle, and the evolution loop IS the verification mechanism.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: perspectives shift via reasoned concession, not averaging
--   The Senior didn't "average" toward TypeScript — they made a specific
--   concession (startup survival > theoretical correctness) with specific
--   conditions (strict config, modular architecture). The Junior didn't
--   abandon Python randomly — they identified a concrete benefit (full-stack
--   career growth). Cell's oracle system forces each revision to justify
--   itself against the disagreement list, preventing mindless convergence.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: supermajority emerged from asymmetric concession costs
--   The CTO and Investor held firm (low concession cost — their position was
--   already popular). The Senior made a large concession (Rust → TypeScript)
--   but extracted conditions. The Junior made a medium concession (Python →
--   TypeScript) for career benefits. The negotiation reflects real-world
--   dynamics: parties with more at stake negotiate harder for conditions.
